PNEUMONIA - USA: (PENNSYLVANIA) CAUSE UNKNOWN, YOUNG ADULTS, 2015-2016, REQUEST FOR INFORMATION
***********************************************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Thu 2 Nov 2017, 4:53 PM
Source: Times Online [edited]
http://www.timesonline.com/news/20171102/medexpress-pneumonia-cases-among-young-adults-on-rise


MedExpress locations in the 9-county region including Beaver County have been inundated with 74 percent more cases of young adults with pneumonia between 2015 and 2016, and that rising trend is expected to continue.

Diana Burick, a physician's assistant at the MedExpress Center Township office, said college-aged individuals, those ages 18 to 25, are more susceptible to illnesses like pneumonia for variety of reasons. "You're thinking of folks that live in crowded conditions, like dorms. You're thinking of folks with maybe less than optimal eating habits, less than optimal sleep habits. Folks that maybe aren't practicing the best hand hygiene," Burick said. Those who smoke or have asthma also have an increased risk of contracting the flu or pneumonia. Pneumonia is an infection that can cause fluid buildup in the lungs, and in severe cases can cause breathing difficulties.

According to the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, there were 184 individuals ages 15 to 24 in the United States who died from influenza and pneumonia in 2015, which is a small fraction of the more than 57 000 people who died from influenza and pneumonia among all ages that year.

And MedExpress locations in the area have already seen more pneumonia cases this year [2017] than in all of 2016. Symptoms can sometimes vary with pneumonia, and it can evolve from the flu due to a compromised immune system.

"When you're thinking of the classic symptoms, it's a cough that is persistent, and you're thinking of a fever. Typically a higher fever within that 100-point mark; most folks tend to have that fatigue, that malaise, just not feeling well sensation," Burick said. "At the same point, it's not always isolation of symptoms. Some people are also coming in with those flu-like symptoms."

The most common form of pneumonia is bacterial, meaning it can be treated with antibiotics. But other forms can be viral or fungal, meaning the illness needs to run its course. The most important thing people should be aware of is prevention techniques, Burick said. "Practicing great hand hygiene, being cautious not to share food or drinks," she said. "It might sound silly, but making sure you're getting adequate sleep and paying attention to your diet."

[Byline: Kate Malongowski]

